<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About this service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">GE Café sits right between GE Profile and Monogram — commercial-inspired styling, matte finishes, customizable hardware. We see it in Pasadena, Glendale, and Studio City kitchens where the owner wanted the Monogram look at a lower price point.</h2>

    <p>Café is the mid-luxury statement tier in GE Appliances' US lineup. Launched 2009, positioned visually between the mainstream Profile line and the panel-ready Monogram top tier, and pitched at the renovation kitchen where the homeowner is investing $30K-$80K in cabinetry and counters and wants the appliance package to read as designer-curated rather than off-the-shelf. The signature design language: matte cabinet finishes in white, black, and slate; commercial-inspired range fronts and refrigerator architecture; and the hardware-customization system — handles and knobs that ship as separate kits in brushed bronze, brushed copper, brushed stainless, and brushed black, swappable at any point in the appliance's life. Practical effect: a Café kitchen photographs distinctively and reads custom, even though the underlying mechanical and electrical architecture shares heavily with Profile and Monogram. That sharing matters when something fails — Café parts availability through GE Appliances' US network is excellent.</p>

    <p>Two Café-specific realities shape every service call we run. First, <strong>Café is part of GE Appliances, which has been Haier-owned since 2016</strong>. Worth saying clearly because Café owners ask about this often: the Haier acquisition did not move design, engineering, or parts distribution overseas. Louisville, Kentucky stays the GE Appliances headquarters, the US engineering teams remain intact, and parts ship through the established GE warehouse network (Louisville, Selmer TN, LaFayette GA, regional distribution centers). Practical service implication: lead times on common Café service parts run 2-5 days, often same-day or next-day on dominant wear items we stock on the truck. Second, <strong>Café is priced $2K-$6K per unit</strong> across the lineup — a French door fridge $3K-$5K, a slide-in range $3K-$5K, a dishwasher $1.4K-$2.2K, a wall oven $3K-$5K. At those replacement price points, repair almost always wins through year 8-10 of service life. We'll tell you when the math gets close (typically a sealed-system or major control-board failure on a year-12+ unit), but the typical Café service call is solidly in repair territory.</p>

    <p>This page covers Café repair across the full US lineup — refrigerators, ranges, wall ovens, dishwashers, cooktops, microwaves, and hood vents. Every Café service call gets a $89 residential diagnostic (applied toward the repair when work is approved), OEM GE parts via the US distribution network, and an honest written quote with parts lead-time disclosed before any work begins.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 REFRIGERATORS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Café refrigerators</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">CVE28 French door fridges anchor the Café refrigerator service mix — and one wear pattern dominates.</h2>

    <p class="lead">The Café French door is the most common Café refrigerator in our LA service area. CVE28DP2NS1 and the surrounding CVE28 production family — counter-depth 28 cu ft French door units with the matte cabinet finishes — show up consistently in renovation kitchens across the territory. Side-by-side and column variants exist in the Café lineup but at lower volume; if you have a Café fridge, statistically it's likely a CVE28.</p>

    <div class="callout-box">
      <h3>2018-2022 CVE28 ice maker auger motor pattern (most common Café service call)</h3>
      <p>The CVE28 French door cohort produced roughly 2018-2022 develops a consistent ice maker auger motor failure around year 3 to 5 of service — and the failure rate runs higher in hard-water LA zip codes, which means most of the inland service area. The San Gabriel Valley (Pasadena, Arcadia, San Marino, San Gabriel itself), the Valley side of the hills (Glendale, Burbank, Studio City, Sherman Oaks, Encino), and the inland Orange County addresses all see harder municipal water than the Westside, mineral buildup loads the auger mechanism faster, and the motor that drives ice from the bin to the dispenser chute fails earlier than it does on Westside installations. Symptoms: ice bin appears full but the dispenser produces nothing, or produces ice intermittently with a grinding sound from inside the door. <strong>Replacement runs $245-$385, often same-day when we stock the CVE28-family auger assemblies on the truck.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <p>Beyond the auger pattern, the Café refrigerator service tree covers a predictable set of items across CVE28 and the side-by-side / column variants:</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Year 2-4:</strong> Water inlet valve ($185-$285) — solenoid at the back of the fridge that admits water to ice maker and dispenser. Failure produces no ice and no dispensed water. Door gasket replacement ($185-$285) on heavily-used French door units.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 3-5:</strong> Ice maker auger motor (above) — the dominant CVE28 service item in hard-water LA.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 5-7:</strong> Evaporator fan motor ($245-$385) — fan runs at reduced RPM, airflow over the evaporator drops, fresh-food compartment can't maintain even temperature. Defrost heater or defrost thermostat ($185-$345) on units that develop ice buildup on the evaporator coil.</li>
      <li><strong>Year 7-10:</strong> Compressor relay ($185-$285), control board ($345-$525), ice maker control module ($185-$345).</li>
      <li><strong>Year 10+:</strong> Compressor or sealed-system work ($580-$880). Worth running repair-vs-replace math at this point on the CVE28 family — Café French door replacement is $3,500-$5,000, repair at $700-$900 is still favorable through year 12.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The matte cabinet finishes (white, black, slate) require non-abrasive cleaning chemistry during service — we don't use stainless-specific polish on matte surfaces. Otherwise the underlying refrigerator architecture (compressor, sealed system, evaporator, control board, ice maker assembly) matches the parts catalog used across the broader GE refrigerator family, including key shared components with GE Profile French door units. That parts-sharing is part of what makes Café service economical.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 RANGES, COOKTOPS, WALL OVENS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Ranges, cooktops, wall ovens</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The Café cooking lineup — commercial-inspired styling, mid-luxury internals.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Café's cooking products are where the commercial-inspired styling reads most clearly. The 30-inch and 36-inch slide-in ranges (gas, induction, and dual-fuel configurations), the pro-style 30-inch and 36-inch gas cooktops with brass burners (CGP9530SLSS and family), induction cooktops (CHP9530SJSS), single and double wall ovens (CTS70DP2NS1, CTS90 advantium with steam), and matte-finish hood vents all share a visual vocabulary while running on GE Appliances' mid-luxury internal platform.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Ranges (C2S, CHS, CGS series)</h3>
        <p>C2S950P2MS1 dual-fuel slide-in (gas cooktop + electric convection oven) and CHS950P2MS1 induction slide-in are the dominant Café ranges. Service items: oven igniter on gas variants ($185-$285) year 3-5 typical, oven control board ($345-$525), surface element on electric/induction variants ($245-$385), door hinge or oven door seal ($185-$285). Convection fan motor ($285-$425) on year 7-9 units.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Cooktops (CGP gas, CHP induction)</h3>
        <p>CGP9530SLSS gas cooktops with the brass-burner pro-styling and CHP9530SJSS induction cooktops. Gas service: igniter ($185-$285), burner valve ($185-$345), spark module ($245-$385). Induction service: surface element ($385-$580 — induction modules cost more than gas valves), control board ($345-$525). Pan-detection failures on induction often resolve with no parts (reset / pan compatibility issue) — diagnostic identifies before parts get quoted.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Wall Ovens (CTS series)</h3>
        <p>CTS70DP2NS1 single wall oven and the CTS double-wall and combination ovens (with advantium speed-cook upper). Service items: oven control board ($345-$525), bake element ($185-$285), broil element ($185-$285), door hinge ($185-$285), oven door seal ($185-$285). Advantium speed-cook upper has its own magnetron and waveguide service tree ($385-$580 typical advantium service).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Hood vents (UVH series)</h3>
        <p>Café matte-finish hood vents in the UVH13013MSS and adjacent series, sized to pair with the 30-inch and 36-inch range and cooktop configurations. Service items: blower motor ($245-$385), LED panel ($185-$285), fan speed control ($185-$285). Lower volume than range/cooktop/wall oven service but recurring across renovation kitchens.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Shared parts with Profile and Monogram</h3>
        <p>Many Café cooking components are shared with GE Profile (igniters, surface elements, oven control boards on certain models) and at the high end of the Café range, with GE Monogram (induction modules, pro-style burner valves). Practical effect: better parts availability than European luxury cooking brands, often same-day or next-day on common service items.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Matte finish care during service</h3>
        <p>The matte cabinet finishes (matte white, matte black, matte slate) need non-abrasive cleaning chemistry. We don't use stainless-specific polish on matte. The handles and knobs (brushed bronze, copper, stainless, black) detach for service work — chassis access doesn't damage the cosmetic hardware.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 DISHWASHERS, MICROWAVES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Dishwashers, microwaves, hardware-customization</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The rest of the Café lineup, and one thing about hardware that's worth knowing.</h2>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Dishwashers (CWB70, CDT875 series)</h3>
        <p>CWB70SP3MD1 stainless-interior third-rack dishwashers and CDT875P2NS1 with the matte-finish exterior. Service items: drain pump ($245-$385) year 4-6 typical, circulation pump ($385-$580), water inlet valve ($185-$285), heating element ($245-$385), control board ($345-$525), door latch ($185-$285), door seal ($185-$285). Third-rack mechanism on the upper-tier models can develop alignment issues — service ($145-$245 labor-only often resolves).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Microwaves (PVM, advantium series)</h3>
        <p>PVM9005SJSS over-the-range and built-in advantium speed-cook units. Microwave service tree: magnetron ($385-$580), waveguide cover, door switch ($185-$285), turntable motor ($185-$285), control panel ($345-$525). Advantium dual-mode (microwave + halogen + convection) has additional service items on the halogen and convection sides — diagnostic identifies which mode is failing before parts get quoted.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Hardware customization is cosmetic, not functional</h3>
        <p>The handles and knobs (brushed bronze, copper, stainless, black) are shipped as separate kits and swap freely. Repair work doesn't require matching hardware to do — hardware detaches, chassis work happens, hardware reattaches. If you want to change finish during service, the kits order through GE Appliances or authorized Café dealers; we can coordinate.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Café vs Profile vs Monogram — quick framing</h3>
        <p>Profile = mid-tier, mainstream luxury, conventional appearance, fixed hardware, priced below Café. Café = mid-luxury, commercial-inspired styling, matte finishes, customizable hardware, the kitchen-photo statement tier. Monogram = full luxury, panel-ready built-in, competes with Sub-Zero/Wolf, priced significantly above Café. Many parts shared across all three.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Honest repair-vs-replace math</h3>
        <p>Café units run $2K-$6K each (fridge $3K-$5K, range $3K-$5K, dishwasher $1.4K-$2.2K, wall oven $3K-$5K). At typical service price points ($200-$600 per repair), repair almost always wins through year 8-10. We tell you when math gets close at year 12+, but that's not the typical Café call.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Parts and lead-time</h3>
        <p>GE Appliances US distribution network — Louisville KY headquarters, Selmer TN, LaFayette GA, regional warehouses. Common Café wear parts (CVE28 auger motors, igniters, water valves, control boards) on the truck. Less-common items 2-5 days. Haier ownership (since 2016) did not affect the parts pipeline; service availability remains among the best in the industry.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 MODELS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">05, Models we service most often</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Café model families in heavy SoCal service rotation.</h2>

    <p class="lead">A representative sample of Café model families our techs service routinely. Not exhaustive — the full Café catalog covers more variants — but covers the units that show up most often on our route.</p>

    <div class="model-grid">
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>French Door Refrigerators (CVE28 series)</h3>
        <p class="model-list">CVE28DP2NS1 · CVE28DP4NW1 · CVE28DM5NS5</p>
        <p>Counter-depth 28 cu ft French door, the dominant Café refrigerator. The 2018-2022 cohort is the ice maker auger motor pattern in hard-water zip codes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Slide-In Ranges (C2S, CHS series)</h3>
        <p class="model-list">C2S950P2MS1 · CHS950P2MS1 · CHS900P2MS1</p>
        <p>Dual-fuel and induction slide-in ranges, 30-inch. C2S = gas cooktop + electric convection oven. CHS = induction.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Wall Ovens (CTS series)</h3>
        <p class="model-list">CTS70DP2NS1 · CTS90DP3MD1 · CTD70DP2NS1</p>
        <p>Single, double, and advantium combination wall ovens. CTS90 advantium pairs convection bake with speed-cook upper.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Dishwashers (CWB, CDT series)</h3>
        <p class="model-list">CWB70SP3MD1 · CDT875P2NS1 · CDT875M5NS5</p>
        <p>Third-rack dishwashers with stainless or matte interior. CDT875 carries the matte-finish exterior; CWB70 the standard stainless.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Cooktops (CGP gas, CHP induction)</h3>
